		<h3>What Makes our Brew System Unique?</h3>

		<p>At the Elora Brewing Company we use a 4 vessel Brewhouse.  With great versatility, this allows us to create several different kinds of beer with only 1 Mash.  Sound confusing?  Check out our interactive flow chart below.</p>

		<h4>Step 1.</h4>

		<p>Select barley, wheat, rye, and other grains are ground into coarser flour called Grist. The grist auger carries the grist across to the main building, overhead and drops it directly into the Mash Tun, wetting the grist and turning it into Mash.</p>

		<h4>Step 2.</h4>

		<p>The mash continues to fall into the Mash Tun, where it is mixed to prevent &#8216;grist ball&#8217; formation. The temperature is carefully controlled to achieve the appropriate enzyme action for our desired brew.</p>

		<h4>Step 3.</h4>

		<p>Upon completion of mash conversion, the mash is pumped into the Lauter Tun, where, after brief Vorlaufing, the nutrient rich fluid - Wort - is separated from the solid material, and sent to one of two Kettle Whirlpools.</p>

		<h4>Step 4.</h4>

		<p>Simultaneously, a second mash can be mashed in. As the wort is extracted, the mash in the lauter tun is Sparged to continue extracting weaker runnings. If a strong beer is desired, the weak runnings may be diverted to the second kettle whirlpool, leaving the first undiluted. This Process is called Partigyle Brewing.</p>
