		<h4>Step 5.</h4>

		<p>If a regular strength beer is desired, all wort will go to the same kettle, and the second mash, once lautering begins can be diverted to the second kettle/whirlpool, and a third mash can be mashed in while the first brew boils away.</p>

		<h4>Step 6.</h4>

		<p>During the boil, hops are added at the beginning to contribute bitterness, and closer to the end to contribute flavour and aroma. Reduction also takes place during the boil, concentrating the nutrients, and caramelization of the sugars darkens the color ever so slightly. Most importantly though, the wort is sterilized.</p>

		<h4>Step 7.</h4>

		<p>Towards the end of the boil, the wort is spun, creating a whirlpool effect, forcing the heavier Trub content to accumulate and settle in the centre of the tank. After brief settling, the scalding hot wort is sent through a two stage Heat Exchanger. Cold water from the Cold Liquor Tank absorbs the bulk of the heat from the wort, and is returned to the hot liquor tank. The near cool wort is then further chilled with cold propylene glycol to a desired temperature dictated by what beer is being made.</p>
	</div>
	<div class="grid__item medium-up--one-half">

		<h4>Step 8.</h4>

		<p>The wort is then sent to the sterile fermenter, where is is pitched with fresh yeast, kick starting the fermentation, where all the sugars liberated in the mash conversion are converted to alcohol and CO2. Over the following 10-20 days, the wort gradually turns to beer, and once it has, it is crash cooled to about 0 degrees celsius. The beer then ages several weeks, during which time, the flavours mellow out, and green beer matures to ready beer.</p>

		<h4>Step 9.</h4>

		<p>Once the yeast has all but dropped out of the beer, the beer is racked or filtered, to a packaging tank, where it is carbonated and ready to keg, at which point it is ready to tap, pour and consume!</p>

		<h4>Step 10.</h4>

		<p>Mmmmmmm&#8230;&#8230;..fresh craft beer made 20 meters from where you are sitting. Enjoy!</p>
